Project/Artifact: Panbo Daily
Description: Since I was now focusing on Panbo full-time I needed to upgrade my application development skills. Particularly in full-stack development. Previously all of my applications were created using Firebase which was client-side rendered and had no backend (all of my api keys were public... I know crazy right!). I also wanted to reduce my reliance on Google who's tools got very expensive. Anyways I decided to learn Next.js to finally upgrade my skills so I could consider myself a real software engineer and also make our applications more efficient and resilient. So I developed a custom full-stack team task tracker, blending features from Asana and BeReal, with AI-powered capabilities. Each Panbo co-founder updates their account daily, sharing their plans for the day, reflecting on their mindset, and listing the tasks they aim to complete. Throughout the day, they update their progress by marking tasks as 'completed.' At the end of each week, content from all team members is analyzed by an LLM, generating concise summaries for newsletters, weekly team meetings, and archiving for future reference. The theory is building in public and keeping the world up to date with Panbo activity. This application is built with Next.js, JavaScript, TailwindCSS, Shadcn/ui, Next Authentication, PostgreSQL relational database, and image uploading with UploadThing. Since its completition on August 1, 2024 we have used Panbo Daily every week meaning 400+ reflections and 1700+ tasks completed.

The program was used by anyone and everyone in the Point Breeze community. This application uses Typescript, Next.js, TailwindCSS, Shadcn/ui, PostgreSQL relational database, Prisma,  and Next/auth. Project/Artifact: Venture Capital Fundraising Analysis
Description: In this project, I analyzed funding deals in the venture capital (VC) industry, with a focus on understanding deal size patterns across different startup stages, industries, and locations. The goal was to uncover trends in how deal sizes vary as startups progress through funding rounds (A, B, C, D), and to investigate how sectors like energy, technology, and hardware influence the amount of capital raised.
Key findings include:
Employee count was the most powerful predictor of deal size.
Energy companies tend to receive larger funding amounts, on average, when outliers are normalized.
Industries like "Business Products and Services" and "Information Technology" dominate in terms of the number of startups securing deals.
Mergers and Acquisitions (M&A) yield more consistent deal sizes than IPOs, which are traditionally seen as the "final" funding round.
I was able to capture 61% of the variation in deal sizes using startup attributes and information leading up to the funding deal.
The project also sheds light on the lack of standardized and consistent data in the VC space, with many deals lacking thorough documentation and transparency. This inconsistency, compounded by self-reported data and high barriers to acquiring accurate information, makes it challenging to draw definitive conclusions.
Despite these challenges, this analysis contributes to a deeper understanding of the VC landscape, providing valuable insights for startup founders seeking funding and investors looking to navigate the complex venture capital ecosystem.

Data Size: ~400,000 rows
Completion Date: 2022-12-01T05:00:00

Project/Artifact: Mass Shooting Factors Analysis
Description: Conducted a comprehensive data analysis of US mass shootings (1966-2022) to identify patterns, risk factors, and impacts. Leveraged statistical modeling and data visualization to extract insights from complex, multidimensional datasets.
Skills Demonstrated

Advanced Statistical Analysis: Applied regression modeling and feature engineering to identify significant predictors
Data Visualization: Created insightful visualizations to reveal patterns in perpetrator demographics, victim characteristics, and temporal trends
Financial Market Analysis: Examined stock price impacts on gun manufacturers following mass shooting events
Cross-domain Research: Integrated psychological, sociological, and economic perspectives through quantitative methods

Key Findings

Identified that 81% of perpetrators exhibited observable crisis signs before incidents, suggesting intervention opportunities
Discovered significant differences in casualty rates between weapon types (assault weapons caused 5× more injuries than handguns)

Project/Artifact: National Leadership and Character Symposium
Description: Attended a 3-day conference at the United States Air Force Academy where I immersed in the life of a cadet, staying in the dorms, eating in the mess hall, and sitting in on classes. At the beginning of the conference I was paired with a USAFA  student and instructured to never leave their sight for the remainder of the conference. This experience opened my eyes to the experiences of service-minded students dedicating their lives to the service of their country. Notable speakers included USA Gold Medalist Missy Franklin, United Airlines CEO Scott Kirby, Astronaut Dr. Kjell Lindgren, and Air Force and Chief of Staff of the US Air Force, and the Chief Master SGT. of the Space Force. The theme of the symposium was "Valuing Human Conditions, Cultures and Societies." This was of interest to me and certainly subverted my expectations for a conference organized by the military. A quote from Scott Kirby stands out for me "It's not that other's don't have the ability it's because they don't have the opportunity." Not everyone has the luck to be given a chance. If you are a person who is given one of those chances it should be your duty to give it to others later on. This conference was eye opening and informative. An interesting note is that very few people in the Air Force have an interest in becoming cybserurity professionals (naturally everyone wants to be a pilot), but the I feel as though the lack of interest is a bit considering where I would assume warfare is going...

Class: Creative Design & Engineering
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**

Class: Web Page Design

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Energy and work

Class: Start Your Own Business
Term: FULL

An introductory course in business technology designed to build foundational skills in digital tools and entrepreneurship. Students developed proficiency in Microsoft Office applications while creating and managing a virtual restaurant business using simulation software. - Basics of networking and IT infrastructure

Class: AP Statistics
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**

Students learned theoretical statistical methods and applied them to real-world data and scenarios, preparing for the AP Statistics exam through both conceptual understanding and practical application.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Exploratory data analysis  
- Designing and planning studies  
- Probability theory and modeling  
- Statistical inference and hypothesis testing  
- Applying statistics to real-life examples  
- Interpreting and communicating data-driven insights

Class: AP Physics
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
An advanced, lab-based physics course that builds on core mechanics concepts while introducing electricity, waves, and fluid dynamics. Designed to prepare students for the AP Physics I exam, the course emphasizes inquiry-based learning through hands-on labs and projects. Additional topics from AP Physics II, such as thermodynamics and optics, are also introduced for deeper exploration.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Mechanics: forces, acceleration, momentum, energy, rotational motion  
- Electricity and electrostatics  
- Electromagnetic waves and sound  
- Simple harmonic motion  
- Fluids and buoyancy  
- Thermodynamics, reflection, and refraction  
- Lab experimentation and scientific inquiry  
- AP Physics I & partial AP Physics II exam preparation

Class: AP US History
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A college-level course that spans American history from pre-revolutionary times to the Reagan era, emphasizing interpretation, analysis, and critical thinking. Students engage with primary and secondary sources to explore key historical events and themes, preparing for the AP exam through advanced content, reading, and writing assignments.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Analysis of key events in U.S. history  
- Use of primary and secondary historical sources  
- College-level reading and writing skills  
- Interpretation of historical documents and perspectives  
- Preparation for the AP United States History exam  
- Critical thinking and historical inquiry

Class: AP Language & Composition
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A year-long Advanced Placement course focused on developing advanced reading and writing skills through the study of a wide range of prose, poetry, and classical texts. Students engage in deep analysis of language and rhetorical strategies, preparing for the AP exam with regular essays, in-depth class discussions, and presentations. Emphasis is placed on rhetorical analysis, persuasion, and synthesis.

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Reading and analyzing non-fiction, poetry, and classic literature (*The Scarlet Letter*, *Death of a Salesman*, *The Great Gatsby*, *Catcher in the Rye*)

- Collaboration and project management  
- Use of advanced manufacturing equipment  
- Problem-solving and prototyping  
- Responsibility and accountability in group work  
- Real-world manufacturing processes

Class: Multi-Material Fabriaction
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A project-based course where students apply skills from previous coursework to create an individual project of their choice. Emphasizing planning, critical thinking, and problem-solving, students design and construct their unique projects, utilizing a variety of materials, textiles, and machines throughout the production process.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Individual project design and development  
- Critical thinking and problem-solving  
- Project planning and management  
- Use of diverse materials and textiles  
- Operation of various production machines  
- Hands-on construction and fabrication

Class: AP Psychology
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A college-level introduction to the systematic study of human and animal behavior and mental processes. Students explore the core principles, facts, and phenomena of psychology across various subfields, while learning about the ethical considerations and methods psychologists use in research and practice.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Major subfields of psychology  
- Psychological principles and phenomena  
- Research methods in psychology  
- Ethical issues in psychological practice  
- Scientific study of behavior and mental processes  
- Critical thinking and analysis in psychological contexts

Class: AP Calculus
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
An advanced course building on AB-level calculus concepts and applying them to more complex problem-solving scenarios. Students engage in theorem proofing, practice AP Calculus exam questions, and study BC-level topics such as integration by parts, lengths of parametric, vector, and polar curves, as well as Maclaurin and Taylor series.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Advanced problem-solving in calculus  
- Integration by parts and related techniques  
- Lengths of parametric, vector, and polar curves  
- Maclaurin and Taylor series  
- Theorem proofing and mathematical rigor  
- Preparation for the AP Calculus BC exam

Class: AP Environmental Science
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A hands-on, inquiry-based course where students explore the interrelationships of the natural world through lab investigations and field work. Key concepts include energy transfer, interactions between earth systems, species-environment interactions, and sustainability.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Energy transfer in ecosystems  
- Earth system interactions  
- Species-environment relationships  
- Sustainability and environmental impact  
- Fieldwork and lab-based inquiry  
- Critical thinking and environmental problem-solving

Class: AP Literature
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A rigorous, college-level course focused on world literature, literary criticism, and composition. Designed for motivated 12th-grade students, the course covers various genres, including poetry, short stories, drama, and novels. Students engage in extensive reading, research, and writing assignments, culminating in the AP English Literature exam in the spring. - Analysis of world literature across genres  
- Literary criticism and research-based writing  
- Writing critical papers using primary and secondary sources  
- Weekly assignments and in-depth reading  
- Preparation for the AP English Literature exam  
- Advanced writing and analytical skills

Class: Multi-Material Fabrication
Term: FULL
Description: **Description:**  
A project-based course where students apply knowledge and skills from previous coursework to design and create a unique individual project. The course emphasizes planning, critical thinking, and problem-solving as students work through the design and construction process. Class: Business Economics
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**

Microeconomics focuses on household and firm behavior, examining how decisions impact market outcomes and when government intervention may improve or harm the free market. Topics include the effects of taxes, minimum wages, subsidies, and antitrust regulation. Macroeconomics looks at the economy as a whole, exploring economic size, unemployment, inflation, and policy options available to the government and Federal Reserve. The course also covers the ongoing impact of the coronavirus on the global and domestic economy. Students will learn to "think like an economist," becoming more informed citizens and voters.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Microeconomic theory: market efficiency, government intervention  
- Economic analysis of real-world issues (e.g., gas taxes, minimum wage)  
- Macroeconomic concepts: economic size, unemployment, inflation  
- Government and Federal Reserve policies  
- International economics and economic data interpretation  
- Critical thinking and analysis from an economic perspective

Class: Ethics and Social Responsibility

Students will be introduced to prominent post-Enlightenment moral and political philosophy, providing a foundational knowledge base. Additionally, the course focuses on improving analytic, critical thinking, and writing skills, teaching logic and tools for constructing and evaluating arguments.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Ethical decision-making frameworks for real-world issues  
- Exploration of post-Enlightenment moral and political philosophy  
- Logical reasoning and argument construction  
- Critical thinking and evaluation of philosophical arguments

Class: Physics Principles I
Term: SPRING

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Particle and rigid body motion  
- Conservation laws and symmetry principles  
- Gravitation and harmonic motion  
- Problem-solving using calculus in mechanics  
- Real-world applications of mechanical principles

Class: Business Statistics
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**

Starting with a simple regression model, the course will primarily focus on multiple regression and logistic regression, which are essential tools in statistical analysis and modeling.

- Logistic regression and its applications  
- Time series analysis and forecasting  
- Statistical modeling techniques for data analysis  
- Interpretation and application of regression results

Class: Accounting & Financial Reports
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**

It emphasizes the analysis and evaluation of accounting information for both investors and managers in the context of planning, decision-making, and control. The course provides an overview of financial accounting, external reporting, and the basic accounting concepts and principles. Key topics include the structure of the income statement, balance sheet, and statement of cash flows, as well as the analysis of common business transactions like credit sales, manufacturing, financing, and obligations to stakeholders. This course is essential for those pursuing careers in investment banking, financial analysis, consulting, management, or entrepreneurship.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Basic accounting concepts and principles  
- Structure of financial statements (income statement, balance sheet, cash flow statement)  
- Accounting for common business transactions (sales, manufacturing, procurement, financing)  
- Analysis of debt, equity, and obligations towards stakeholders  
- Evaluation and use of financial information for investment decisions  
- Understanding of accounting for business strategy and management

Class: Faces of Jihad in African Islam
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**  
This course provides a broad understanding of the history of Islam in Africa, focusing primarily on West Africa while also examining developments in the northern and eastern regions. The course explores Islam not just as a religious practice, but also as an ideology and tool for social change. It covers the processes of Islamization across the continent, delving into various Islamic experiences, including Islamist militancy. Topics include prophetic jihad, jihad of the pen, jihad of the soul, and the evolving meanings of jihad from the 7th century to contemporary global jihadism in sub-Saharan Africa.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- History of Islam in Africa, with a focus on West Africa  
- Islamization processes and their impact on African societies  
- Islamic ideologies and their role in social change  
- Analysis of jihad, from prophetic to contemporary global jihadism  
- The role of Islam in shaping political and social movements across Africa  
- Examination of Islamist militancy and its influence on African regions

Class: Corporate Finance
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**  
This in-depth course introduces the foundations of finance with a focus on applications crucial for corporate managers. The course emphasizes the process of valuation, which is central to financial decision-making both within firms and in interactions with investors. Students will explore a variety of financial decisions, including investment criteria, asset and liability valuation, risk-return relationships, capital structure choices, and payout policies. The course also covers the effective use and valuation of derivative securities such as futures, options, and convertible securities, along with risk management strategies.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Valuation of financial assets and liabilities  
- Investment decision-making criteria  
- Risk and return relationships  
- Capital structure choices and payout policy  
- Valuation and use of derivative securities (futures, options, convertible securities)  
- Risk management techniques and strategies  
- Financial decision-making within a corporate context

Class: Business Communication for Impact

Drawing on feedback from employers, employees, alumni, and past students, this course is designed to equip you with the skills necessary to succeed in all types of communication: spoken and written, formal and informal, prepared and spontaneous, both online and in person.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Effective spoken and written communication  
- Formal and informal communication strategies  
- Prepared and spontaneous communication techniques  
- Online and in-person communication practices  
- Communication strategies for educational, professional, and personal contexts

Class: How to Make Things

The projects include a 2D Design, 3D Design, and a final "Micro-Manufacturing" project. Students will gain a wide variety of design, engineering, and fabrication skills through the new Studios @ Tangen Hall. The final project tasks interdisciplinary student teams with creating a "micro-business," where they will design and use 3D printed molding and casting techniques to produce a small-scale run of functional products. Class: Strategic Cost Analysis
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
Increasing business competition requires organizations to develop achievable strategies while analyzing goals in financial terms to evaluate performance. Organizational efficiency hinges on viewing all spending as an investment, making decisions based on strategic vision and the ability to derive value from each investment. Managers must analyze decisions from a financial perspective, gain insight into resource deployment across the organization, and leverage cost analysis for strategic success. 

Strategic Cost Analysis focuses on managing and analyzing costs to enhance the organization's strategic position. By understanding which activities and costs support the organization's strategy, managers can focus on reducing or eliminating those that add little value, while boosting investments in activities that strengthen the strategy. This approach helps improve strategic performance by continuously evaluating and ensuring that actions taken are yielding the desired outcomes.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Strategic cost analysis and management  
- Financial decision-making and analysis  
- Evaluating organizational efficiency and performance  
- Aligning spending with strategic goals  
- Cost reduction strategies  
- Identifying activities that add or detract from strategic value  
- Performance evaluation and strategic positioning

Class: Managerial Economics
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This course introduces managerial economics, applying microeconomic theory to managerial decision-making. Microeconomic theory is invaluable for understanding the behavior of individuals and firms across various economic contexts. The course aims to equip you with the tools to effectively analyze managerial and business problems within an economic framework.

While the course is focused on practical tools, it also explores real-world business applications, demonstrating the value of these tools and enabling you to develop skills for using them. Unlike traditional microeconomic theory courses, the focus is on prescriptive analysis: What should a manager do to achieve a specific objective? This complements the descriptive aspects of economics: Why do firms and consumers behave as they do? Both perspectives are essential for formulating optimal strategies.

The course begins with the theory of supply and demand, forming the foundation of the competitive model. This model is used as a benchmark for evaluating other market structures. Understanding demand is crucial for firm decisions related to pricing, marketing, and product positioning, while supply helps frame decisions about costs and investments. The course then moves to more complex market structures like monopoly and oligopoly, commonly encountered by real-world firms.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Application of microeconomic theory to managerial decisions  
- Analyzing supply and demand in competitive and non-competitive markets  
- Pricing, marketing, and product positioning strategies  
- Firm cost structures and investment decisions  
- Strategic decision-making in monopoly and oligopoly contexts  
- Prescriptive versus descriptive economics for decision-making

Class: Investment Management

The course explores a wide range of topics including asset allocation, diversification, long-short strategies, factor models, long-horizon investing, portfolio optimization, sustainable (ESG) investing, hedge funds, mutual funds, behavioral finance, performance evaluation, trading, and simulation. The focus is on investment strategies and portfolio management rather than security valuation or discretionary equity research.

**Key Topics & Skills:**  
- Asset allocation and diversification strategies  
- Long-short strategies and factor models  
- Long-horizon investing and portfolio optimization  
- Sustainable (ESG) investing and its impact  
- Understanding hedge funds and mutual funds  
- Behavioral finance and its influence on investment decisions  
- Performance evaluation and trading techniques  
- Investment simulations and practical applications

Class: Probability

It emphasizes practical applications and statistical analysis, equipping students with essential skills for decision-making and problem-solving.

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Conditional probability and Bayes' rule  
- Discrete and continuous random variables  
- Expectation, variance, and standard deviation  
- Moment generating functions  
- Joint distributions and correlation  
- Laws of large numbers and central limit theorem

Class: Game Theory for Business and Life

This course enhances strategic thinking through the lens of game theory, which helps you make intelligent and creative decisions in interactions with others. While focusing on business applications, game theory is also explored in politics, international relations, sports, and everyday life, equipping you with tools to navigate complex, competitive situations.

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Application of game theory in business, politics, and other fields

Students explore various finance areas such as FinTech, asset management, corporate finance, and venture capital, focusing on how big data and analytics are revolutionizing the field. The course equips students with the skills to improve financial decision-making and serves as a foundation for finance-related data analytics roles, both within and outside the sector.

Class: Internet Law, Privacy, and Cybersecurity

Students will examine federal and state regulations, data breaches, online privacy protections, and the legal challenges of managing a borderless Internet. The course also covers the liabilities of intermediaries like network operators, social media platforms, and search engines.

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Data breaches and online privacy protections  
- Managing the borderless Internet legally  
- Legal liabilities of intermediaries (network operators, social media, search engines)

Class: Teamwork and Interpersonal Influence

Focusing on influence, leadership, team dynamics, and ethics, students will learn how to thrive in organizations and lead teams toward achieving shared goals. The course includes a "drill down" approach that examines organizational, team, and individual levels of behavior, using experiential exercises, simulations, and group discussions.

**Key Topics & Skills:**

- Team decision-making and overcoming challenges

Class: Modern Data Mining
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**

Students will learn key methods such as regression, classification, and penalized regression, with an emphasis on model building, evaluation, and advanced topics like deep learning, using R for practical applications.

- Working with SQL databases  
- Data wrangling, reshaping, and summarizing

Class: Forensic Analytics

Description: **Description:**  
This course provides hands-on experience with Big Data and predictive analytics for financial applications. Students will learn to manipulate large-scale financial databases and build predictive models to make strategic and investment decisions. The course focuses on forensic analytics, covering three key applications: forecasting future earnings, predicting accounting fraud, and detecting insider trading. Students will gain SQL coding skills to work with Big Data, leveraging Wharton Research Data Services for analysis and computation.

- Forecasting future earnings and predicting accounting fraud  
- Detecting insider trading through analytics  
- SQL programming for Big Data manipulation  
- Introduction to forensic analytics and predictive modeling

Class: Media Culture & Society in Contempory China
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This course explores contemporary Chinese media, culture, and society, examining the significant transformations in China since the late 1970s. Emphasizing media, students will analyze the causes and consequences of these changes, utilizing concepts and theories from sociology, communication, and other fields. The course focuses on the interplay of structural, institutional forces and individual agency, and encourages a pluralistic view of the narratives surrounding China. Students will develop critical skills in social science analysis, particularly in the study of media and social change, and apply these skills to broader cultural and societal contexts.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Informed and critical analysis of contemporary Chinese media and society  
- Understanding social change through a historical and theoretical lens  
- Application of sociological and communication theories  
- Exploration of structural and institutional forces vs. individual agency

Class: International Business Ethics
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This course introduces students to international business ethics, focusing on the moral responsibilities of businesses operating across national borders. Key questions include: What does it mean to be a moral corporate leader or consumer in a global context? How do international dynamics shape our moral obligations, especially regarding issues like climate change, human rights, and poverty? Through case studies and discussions, students will develop the skills to analyze complex ethical issues, engage in thoughtful debate, and construct well-reasoned oral and written arguments.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Analyzing moral responsibilities in international business  
- Understanding the global context of ethical decision-making  
- Addressing corporate responsibilities in cross-national issues  
- Engaging in productive discussions on controversial topics  
- Advancing clear, well-defended arguments in both oral and written formats

Class: Venture Acceleration Lab
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This lab provides experiential learning by engaging with live startup ventures. The primary goal is to accelerate the development of ventures through a structured environment where industry mentors guide entrepreneurs. Students—undergraduates and MBAs—learn by witnessing mentor-entrepreneur interactions and by assisting in the development of value creation and capture strategies for startups. The lab brings together founders, students, mentors, and specialists, providing a unique opportunity for collaboration. Students will actively contribute to early-stage ventures, helping them structure and refine their business strategies.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Accelerating startup venture development  
- Mentorship in early-stage entrepreneurship  
- Structuring value creation and capture strategies  
- Collaborating with startup founders, mentors, and specialists  
- Hands-on experience with live cases from early-stage ventures  
- Participating in "super" sessions for feedback and development priorities

Class: Big Data Analytics
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**  
In this course, students learn to scale data analytics to handle large volumes of data using statistical machine learning techniques across multiple compute nodes. The focus is on data collection, cleaning, integration, and processing, leveraging parallel computation. Students will explore popular distributed frameworks and tools for big data analysis, including graph analysis, clustering, classification, and more. The course equips students with the skills to handle data efficiently and apply machine learning techniques in real-world, big data contexts.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- **Big Data Analytics:** Techniques for modeling, cleaning, and integrating large datasets.  
- **Data Wrangling & Acquisition:** Techniques for obtaining and structuring data from various sources (e.g., HTML, XML).  
- **Data Transformation & Cleaning:** Operations like filtering, aggregating, and ensuring data quality (ETL).  
- **Machine Learning:** Supervised and unsupervised learning methods (clustering, classification, regression).  
- **Neural Networks & Deep Learning:** Multi-layer networks, backpropagation, and CNNs.  
- **Stream Processing:** Real-time data processing with platforms like Apache Spark Streaming.  
- **Distributed Data & Systems:** Consistency, transactions, and scaling in distributed environments.  
- **Data Archival & Provenance:** Using data lakes and ensuring reproducibility.

**Key Technologies:**
- **Python:** For data processing, machine learning, and visualization (e.g., Pandas, Scikit-learn).  
- **SQL:** Querying and managing large datasets.  
- **Apache Spark:** Distributed data processing for big data analytics.  
- **PyTorch:** Building and training neural networks.  
- **AWS/Cloud Computing:** Using cloud services for data storage and processing.  
- **Jupyter Notebooks:** Hands-on coding and data analysis.

Class: Computer Animation
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**  
This course focuses on 2D and 3D computer animation through a series of studio projects. Students will develop skills in time-based design and storytelling, enhancing their sensitivity to movement, cinematography, editing, sound, color, and lighting. The course will also cover compositing software, allowing students to combine 2D graphics, 3D animation, and sound to create compelling visual narratives.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- 2D and 3D computer animation  
- Time-based design and storytelling  
- Cinematography, editing, sound, color, and lighting  
- Compositing software for integrating 2D, 3D, and sound

Class: Monetary Economics and the Global Economy
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**  
Finance 101 is an intermediate-level course in macroeconomics, focusing on business cycles, monetary and fiscal policy, and international trade. The course aims to provide a unified framework for analyzing macroeconomic trends, business cycles, and macroeconomic policy, with applications to current events. Key topics include long-term economic growth, financial crises (e.g., 08/09 Financial Crisis, COVID recession), and policy changes such as interest rates, government expenditure, and taxes. The course is structured into measurement, long-run economic performance, business cycles, macroeconomic policy, and institutions, with a special emphasis on real-time analysis of macroeconomic events and their impact on financial markets.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Business cycles and macroeconomic trends  
- Monetary and fiscal policy  
- Economic indicators (GDP, unemployment, inflation)  
- Short-run fluctuations and long-run economic performance  
- Institutions: Federal Reserve and policy decisions  
- Global economic events and their implications

Class: Participatory Cities
Term: FALL
Description: **Description:**  
This course explores the concept of a participatory city—its historical significance, contemporary meaning, and future potential. It examines the role of citizens in co-creating more just cities and communities amidst rising inequality and inequity. The course focuses on how citizens can be engaged in decision-making about urban spaces and how to ensure meaningful inclusion, particularly of historically silenced voices. By connecting theory with praxis, students will learn about the history, challenges, methods, approaches, and impact of community participation and stakeholder involvement in urban development.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Concept and evolution of participatory cities  
- Citizen engagement in urban decision-making  
- Addressing inequality and inequity in cities  
- Methods for ensuring inclusion of marginalized voices  
- History and challenges of community participation in urban planning

Class: Entrepreneurship Launchpad
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This course focuses on the practical aspects of entrepreneurship, with an emphasis on creating a venture that matters to both you and others. It’s designed for students actively working on a venture concept and aims to help make it market-ready. The course provides a roadmap, grounded in the latest academic research, to guide students through key entrepreneurial steps such as validating ideas, building business models, stress testing assumptions, formalizing the venture, and fundraising. The course fosters a collaborative environment, where students help refine each other's ventures, culminating in a pitch competition judged by venture capital investors.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Validating business ideas  
- Developing and refining business models  
- Stress testing assumptions and analyses  
- Formalizing the venture  
- Fundraising strategies beyond venture capital  
- Collaborative entrepreneurship  
- Pitch preparation and presentation

Class: AI, Business, and Society
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This course explores the transformative role of AI technologies in business, labor, and society, emphasizing the societal value they can create and the challenges they may present. Rather than focusing on the technical aspects of AI, the course aims to equip managers and policymakers with the tools to critically assess AI’s impact across various domains such as criminal justice, healthcare, media, and HR. Through technical labs, exams, and presentations, students will learn to navigate the opportunities and challenges posed by AI in decision-making, with a focus on understanding how to address the ethical, legal, and economic challenges as AI becomes integrated into societal decision-making processes.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Understanding AI capabilities and applications  
- Critical assessment of AI's societal impact  
- Identifying legal, ethical, and economic challenges of AI  
- Applying AI in business decision-making  
- Communicating about AI-related issues with stakeholders  
- Hands-on experience with AI technologies through labs

Class: Sports Analytics Capstone
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This capstone course offers a hands-on introduction to the growing field of sports analytics, allowing students to apply their extensive knowledge of data analysis to real sports data sets. The course focuses on solving real-world problems in sports using statistical techniques, while also providing transferable skills applicable to a wide range of industries. While the primary context is sports, the techniques learned are broadly applicable in various domains. Students are expected to have prior experience in statistics or business analytics and will build on their foundational skills through practical application and feedback.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Sports analytics techniques and applications  
- Real-world data analysis in sports  
- Integration of advanced data analysis skills  
- Problem-solving with real sports data sets  
- Transferable skills for diverse industries  
- Feedback-driven learning and refinement of techniques

Class: Urban Education
Term: SPRING
Description: **Description:**  
This seminar explores the persistence of inequality in US schools, particularly urban ones, and examines how education systems must evolve in the informational age to achieve more equitable outcomes. By bridging theory and practice, the course tackles issues of equity in various aspects of education, such as lesson design, curriculum planning, and classroom management. Theoretical frameworks from education, sociology, anthropology, and psychology will be applied to practical areas of education practice.

**Key Topics & Skills:**
- Understanding the reproduction of inequalities in education  
- Examining the role of schools in fostering positive student identities  
- Analyzing the relationship between education systems and equity  
- Exploring curriculum design, school funding, and policy planning  
- Integrating theories from multiple disciplines (education, sociology, psychology, anthropology)  
- Applying theoretical knowledge to practical education settings
